                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/237a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-15T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 15, 1912—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Department feels uneasy about the 200 or more Americans resident in Los
                    Mochis and vicinity. Ascertain whether Mexican Government can send a ship with
                    troops for their protection, and also gain authentic information as to their
                    situation. What does the Mexican Government propose to do to afford protection
                    on the west coast? Is Mexican opinion still so sensitive that the sending of one
                    or two naval vessels to relieve the fears of the American citizens concerned and
                    to afford them refuge if necessary would be misinterpreted to the peril of
                    Americans in Mexico generally?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
